Headline: Q&A: Reddit CEO Steve Huffman says the API was “never designed to support third-party apps” and he didn't know how much they were profiting from Reddit's API
Alphabet plans to wind down Google Domains and sell its assets, including ~10M domains, to Squarespace in Q3 2023, a source says for ~$180M; SQSP jumps 9%+
CISA confirms “several” US federal government agencies “experienced intrusions” in the hack of Progress' MOVEit Transfer tool and is providing support to them
Intel announces its first quantum processor, Tunnel Falls, a 12-qubit chip using electrons for storing data, available to select academic and research partners
The US DOJ charges a Russian national in Arizona for allegedly deploying LockBit ransomware, the third LockBit affiliate the US has charged since November 2022
How Microsoft's bet on OpenAI due to transfer learning, an approach that wasn't yet commercialized, may help Microsoft leapfrog Google and corner the AI market
Sources: Alphabet advises employees not to enter confidential info into chatbots, including Bard, or directly use AI-generated code, following Amazon and others
Twitch launches a Partner Plus tier, offering a 70/30 revenue sharing split to creators who have 350+ recurring paid subscriptions for three consecutive months
Micron plans to invest $603M in a chip packaging facility in Xian, China; the country banned Micron's products from its critical infrastructure in May 2023
Sources: Meta is working on ways to make the next version of LLaMA available for commercial use; the model is currently only licensed for research use
How the “arms race” of SEO experts has left Google Search and the web drowning in garbage text, resulting in customers and businesses failing to find each other
The UK CMA clears Amazon's proposed $1.7B iRobot deal, saying acquiring the robot vacuum maker would have “no impact on competition in the UK”
Amazon officially opens Metropolitan Park in Arlington, Virginia, the first phase of HQ2, where the company has projected bringing 25,000 workers by 2030
Intel plans to invest as much as $4.6B to build a semiconductor assembly and test facility in Wroclaw, Poland, as the EU seeks to boost chip production
